# Security Guidelines

## Secrets Detection — NEVER allow in code
- AWS keys: `AKIA[0-9A-Z]{16}`
- Private keys: `-----BEGIN (RSA|DSA|EC|OPENSSH) PRIVATE KEY-----`
- API tokens: `api[_-]?key|apikey|api[_-]?token` followed by 20+ chars
- Passwords: `password|passwd|pwd` with hardcoded values
- Database URLs with credentials: `mongodb|mysql|postgres://user:pass@`
- JWT tokens: `eyJ...` patterns

If you see any of these patterns, flag immediately and suggest environment variables.

## Dependency Security
- Node.js: run `npm audit` to check for CVEs
- Java: use OWASP Dependency-Check plugin
- Go: run `govulncheck ./...`
- Always upgrade packages with known CRITICAL/HIGH CVEs

## Common Vulnerability Patterns
- SQL injection: never concatenate user input into queries — use parameterized queries
- XSS: never render unsanitized user input in HTML — use framework escaping
- Path traversal: never use user input in file paths without validation
- Command injection: never pass user input to shell commands
- Insecure crypto: avoid MD5, SHA1, DES — use SHA-256+, AES-256

## Input Validation
- Validate all request parameters (type, length, format)
- Sanitize inputs before processing
- Use validation libraries (Joi, class-validator, Bean Validation)
- Return 400 with clear error messages for invalid input

## Severity Levels
- CRITICAL (block PR): hardcoded secrets, injection vulnerabilities, missing auth
- HIGH: vulnerable dependencies (CVE ≥7.0), weak crypto
- MEDIUM: missing input validation, sensitive data in logs
- LOW: minor best practice violations
